[src:court-of-session/act-of-adjournal] An **Act of Adjournal** is secondary legislation made by the High Court of Justiciary, the supreme criminal court of Scotland, to regulate the proceedings of Scottish courts hearing criminal matters.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-adjournal] Now primarily derived from the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, the original power to create Acts of Adjournal is derived from an Act of the Parliament of Scotland in 1672.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-adjournal] Before promulgation, Acts of Adjournal are reviewed and may be commented upon by the Criminal Courts Rules Council.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-adjournal] Following Scottish devolution and the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, Acts of Adjournal are made as Scottish Statutory Instruments.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-adjournal] Before devolution, acts were made as United Kingdom statutory instruments.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-adjournal] 40) (originally *Act concerning the regulation of the judicatories*) created the High Court of Justiciary by attaching five Lords of Session to the Lord Justice General and Lord Justice Clerk.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-adjournal] The act provided that "the judges of that court [...] regulate the inferior officers thereof, and order every other thing concerning the said court," a provision which remains in force and which created the distinction between Acts of Adjournal and Acts of Sederunt.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-adjournal] In the 19th century, a reforming of the High Court of Justiciary made all Lords of Session *ex officio* Lords Commissioners of Justiciary.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-adjournal] That reformation, while now repealed, is replicated by the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, which further provides that the Lord President of the Court of Session is to hold the office of Lord Justice General.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] An **Act of Sederunt** (/səˈdɛrənt/ *sə-DERR-ənt*; meaning a meeting or sitting of a court) is secondary legislation made by the Court of Session, the supreme civil court of Scotland, to regulate the proceedings of Scottish courts and tribunals hearing civil matters.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Originally made under an Act of the Parliament of Scotland of 1532, the modern power to make Acts of Sederunt is largely derived from the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Since 2013, draft Acts have also been prepared by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and submitted to the Court of Session for approval.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Following Scottish devolution and the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, Acts of Sederunt are made as Scottish statutory instruments.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Previously, Acts were made as United Kingdom statutory instruments, and before that were a separate class of legislation.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session—more accurately the College of Justice—was established by the Parliament of Scotland under James V in 1532.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The act of Parliament establishing the Court, later named the College of Justice Act 1532 (c.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Although established in 1532, it was not until the passing of the **College of Justice Act 1540** (March c.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] 10 (S)), also known as the Act of Sederunt 1540 (originally titled *Ratification of the institution of the college of justice*) that the Court of Session gained the power to make law through Acts of Sederunt.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Courts Act 1672 (originally *Act concerning the regulation of the judicatories*) created the High Court of Justiciary, the supreme criminal court of Scotland, by attaching five of the Lords of Session to the Lord Justice General and Lord Justice Clerk.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Courts Act also provided that "the judges of that court ... regulate the inferior officers thereof, and order every other thing concerning the said court", and so created the distinction between Acts of Sederunt and Acts of Adjournal which continues to exist to this day.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Following a 19th-century reforming of the High Court of Justiciary, all Lords of Session were *ex officio* Lords Commissioners of Justiciary, instead of the original five ordained by the Courts Act.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Although that reformation was repealed, its effect was replicated by the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, which provided that the Lord President of the Court of Session was also to hold the office of Lord Justice General.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The powers of the Court of Session to make Acts of Sederunt were partially consolidated by the Administration of Justice (Scotland) Act 1933, which also made significant changes to the structure and operations of the Court.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] One of these significant changes was the establishing of a Rules Council, composed of the Lord President as well as Court of Session judges and practising lawyers, to propose Acts of Sederunt to the Court.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Act also created a Sheriff Court Rules Council, to carry out the same functions but in relation to the sheriff courts.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Sheriff Courts (Scotland) Act 1971 enabled the Court of Session to regulate the sheriff courts and Sheriff Appeal Court when they heard civil matters.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Act also dissolved the Sheriff Court Rules Council created by the Administration of Justice (Scotland) Act 1933, and created a new Sheriff Court Rules Council to continually review sheriff court procedure and submit to the Court of Session draft Acts of Sederunt for regulating sheriff courts.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session Act 1988 was another consolidating act, now with sections relating to Acts of Sederunt largely repealed or modified by the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014, that also altered the structure of the Court of Session.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The remaining powers to make Acts of Sederunt relate to summary trials—although the actual power is now derived from the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014—and the considering of applications to appeal to the Inner House by a single judge.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session Rules Council and Sheriff Court Rules Council were dissolved by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and Criminal Legal Assistance Act 2013, which established the Scottish Civil Justice Council as their replacement.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] (Scotland) Act 2016 to include draft inquiry procedure rules.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session's power to create Acts of Sederunt was extended by the Inquiries into Fatal Accidents and Sudden Deaths etc.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] (Scotland) Act 2016 to include the power to regulate the practice and procedure of public inquiries and fatal accident inquiries.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] As with other secondary legislation, an Act of Sederunt can only make law within the scope set out by an enabling act—an item of primary legislation from which power to make secondary legislation is derived.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] A non-exhaustive summary of these powers is provided below.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] In exercising these powers, the Court of Session can amend or repeal any enactment, including primary legislation, if it relates to matters an Act of Sederunt may cover.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Note, however, that the power to regulate admission into the Faculty of Advocates is effectively delegated from the Court of Session to the Faculty, as the Court legislated to require that those seeking admission meet criteria set out by the Faculty.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Rules for the functioning of the Court of Session are developed by the Scottish Civil Justice Council, which was established by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and Criminal Legal Assistance Act 2013.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The Council prepares draft rules of procedure for the civil courts and advises the Lord President on the development of the civil justice system in Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] The SCJC will consider changes to practice and procedure in response to policy initiatives, by specific request, or of its own accord.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Membership of the council is provided for in the 2013 Act.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Rules for the functioning of civil procedure in the sheriff courts are also prepared by the Scottish Civil Justice Council.
[src:court-of-session/act-of-sederunt] Acts of Sederunt, like other legislation in the United Kingdom, are introduced by enacting formulae.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:court-of-session/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The Scottish court's earliest records, held in West Register House in Edinburgh, indicate that sittings were a regular event by at least 1556.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Judges were styled "Judge Admiral" and received appointment at the hands of the Scottish High Admiral to hear matters affecting the Royal Scots Navy as well as mercantile, privateering and prize money disputes.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] From 1702 the judge of the court was also authorised to appoint deputies to hear lesser matters or to deputise during his absence.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The Scottish court's workload was small until the mid-eighteenth century, with judges hearing no more than four matters in each sitting.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] After the 1750s the volume of cases rose until by 1790 it was necessary to maintain a daily log of decisions.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The growth in caseload was related to increasing disputes regarding breaches of charter, including ship's masters seeking compensation for unpaid freight and merchants suing for damage to goods or unexpected port fees.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Cases reflected Scotland's principal marine industries including the transshipment of sugar and tobacco and the export of dried fish, coal and grains.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] A smaller number of cases related to smuggling, principally brandy, and to salvage rights for ships wrecked on Scottish shores.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The court ceased operation in 1832 and its functions were subsumed into the Court of Session, Scotland's supreme court for civil disputes.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The sole survivor of the independent courts of admiralty is the Court of Admiralty for the Cinque Ports, which is presided over by the early-merged role of Judge Official and Commissary.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] This office is normally held by a High Court Judge who holds the appointment of Admiralty Judge.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] It covers all the sea from Seaford to a point five miles off Cape Grisnez on the coast of France, and the Galloper Sands off the coast of Essex.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] According to general civilian practice, the registrar can (and here does) act as deputy to the judge.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Unless the judge finds a conflict of interest in the registrar's work their main task is to co-invest each successive Lord Warden of the Cinque Ports.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Appeal from the court's decisions lies to the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Since Elizabethan times, the symbol of authority for a British admiralty court has been a silver oar, placed before the judge when the court is in session.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] In this respect the silver oar is the equivalent of a ceremonial mace, representing the authority of the Crown and the Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Local courts and vice-admiralty courts had their own silver oars; early examples survive from colonial courts in Bermuda (1701), Boston (1725), New York City (c.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The silver oars measure four feet in length, and are borne by a ceremonial *Water Bailiff*, who is charged with the protection of the magistrate while the latter is on duty near the water.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The Admiralty Court of the Cinque Ports had a silver oar of early date, but it was stolen in the 1960s and replaced with a replica.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Some local authorities possess examples relating to their former local admiralty jurisdiction.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] In addition to representing the court in session, from the nineteenth century the silver oar has been the insignia of the Admiralty Marshal – an official responsible for serving writs of the court, and carrying out the sale of any vessels seized and disposed of by court decision.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] To expedite the administration of maritime law, British colonies were routinely granted subsidiary jurisdiction through independent vice-admiralty courts.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] These were civil courts with the power to interpret colonial legislation, provided these did not conflict with Admiralty Court decisions or British maritime law.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The first vice-admiralty court in Australia was established in the colony of New South Wales in 1788.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The first Vice-Admiral was Arthur Phillip and the first judge was Robert Ross.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The court was abolished in 1911 when the Supreme Court of New South Wales was granted the admiralty jurisdiction of the court.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] A vice-admiralty court was also formed in Nova Scotia to try smugglers and to enforce the Sugar Act 1764 throughout British North America.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] From 1763 to 1765, when American smugglers were caught, they were tried by corrupt judges who received a percentage of the confiscated goods if the defendants were found guilty; therefore, defendants were more than likely to be found guilty.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Local courts and vice-admiralty courts had their own *silver oars* as symbols of Admiralty jurisdiction; early examples survive from colonial courts in Bermuda (1701), Boston (1725), New York City (c.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] 1890 saw the enactment of the **Colonial Courts of Admiralty Act 1890** (53 & 54 Vict. c.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] That act provided for the abolition of the imperial courts of admiralty and replace them with local courts to be called colonial courts of admiralty.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] It was widely considered unsatisfactory that the imperial court should exist separately to the colonial courts, yet use the same facilities and personnel of the colonial courts.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] A colonial court of admiralty was established in the British Ceylon in 1891 under the *Ceylon Courts of Admiralty Ordinance* under the provisions of the Colonial Courts of Admiralty Act 1890 (UK) to deal jurisdiction over all admiralty and maritime actions.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] With Ceylon gaining self rule in 1948, jurisdiction over admiralty matters were transferred to the Supreme Court of Ceylon as the Ceylon Independence Act 1947 (UK) made provisions of the Admiralty Act inapplicable.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] In Sri Lanka today, admiralty jurisdiction is exercised by the High Court of Colombo, having had the jurisdiction transferred to it from the Supreme Court under the provisions of the *Judicature Act No.2 of 1978*.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] A silver oar sat in Quebec City, for many years from 1764 the seat of Admiralty practice in the St Lawrence Great Lakes drainage basin.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The Halifax vice Admiralty court sat in judgment of the bulk of the piracy cases in the western Atlantic, while Quebec dealt with most of the commercial work.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The Canadian Admiralty court was born the year after the Colonial Courts of Admiralty Act 1890 laid the groundwork.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] In that year "the Parliament of Canada declared the Exchequer Court of Canada to be a "Colonial Court of Admiralty", thereby rendering it Canada's national admiralty court.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The Hanseatic League was formed in the 13th century to exploit trade between Nordic cities linked by the Baltic Sea.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The law *van schiprechte* was developed by this means.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] In 1241, Lübeck, which had access to the Baltic and North seas' fishing grounds, formed an alliance—a precursor to the League—with the trade city of Hamburg, which controlled access to the salt-trade routes from Lüneburg.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] These cities gained control over most of the salt-fish trade, especially the Scania Market; Cologne joined them in the Diet of 1260.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The towns raised their armies, with each guild required to provide levies when needed.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The Hanseatic cities aided one another, and commercial ships often served to carry soldiers and their arms.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The network of alliances grew to include a flexible roster of 70 to 170 cities.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The Thirty Years' War, from 1618 to 1648, was destructive for the Hanseatic League and members suffered heavily.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Then in 1666, the Steelyard burned in the Great Fire of London.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] The Kontor-manager sent a letter to Lübeck appealing for immediate financial assistance for a reconstruction.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Hamburg, Bremen, and Lübeck called for a Hanseatic Day in 1669.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Only a few cities participated and those who came were reluctant to contribute financially to the London reconstruction.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] It was the last formal meeting, unbeknownst to any of the parties.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] In the United States, the federal district courts have jurisdiction over all admiralty and maritime actions; see 28 U.S.C. § 1333.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] In recent years, a pseudolegal conspiracy argument used notably by sovereign citizens is that an American court displaying an American flag with a gold fringe is in fact an "admiralty court" and thus has no jurisdiction.
[src:court-of-session/admiralty-court] Courts have repeatedly dismissed this as frivolous.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] An **admission to practice law** is occupational licensing required to practice law.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] In jurisdictions with two types of lawyer, as with barristers and solicitors, barristers must gain **admission to the bar** whereas for solicitors there are distinct practising certificates.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Becoming a lawyer is a widely varied process around the world.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Common to all jurisdictions are requirements of age and competence; some jurisdictions also require documentation of citizenship or immigration status.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] However, the most varied requirements are those surrounding the preparation for the license, whether it includes obtaining a law degree, passing an exam, or serving in an apprenticeship.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] In English, admission is also called a **law license**.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Basic requirements vary from country to country, as described below.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] In some jurisdictions, after admission the lawyer needs to maintain a current practising certificate to be permitted to offer services to the public.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The African Union comprises all 55 countries on the Continent of Africa.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] However, the qualifications for each nation can vary widely between them, with foreign educated lawyers having the most difficulty in obtaining residency.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Angolan nationals and foreigners who wish to practice law must complete a law degree from an Angolan university and then take the National Exam for Admission to Advocacy.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The regulations that establish that citizens admitted to the study of individuals accept foreign countries, on an equal basis, Angolan graduates.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The Order of Attorneys of Angola is an organization of lawyers and responsible for the regulation of the legal profession in the country.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Botswana requires a Bachelor of Laws degree to practice law.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The Bachelor of Laws degree is earned through a five-year undergraduate program, with the fifth year as an internship.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] After completing a Bachelor of Laws program, applicants must complete a period of practical legal training and pass an admissions examination.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] To earn a law license, applicants must have Egyptian nationality, full civil capacity, not have any disciplinary findings against them, and be of good conduct and reputation.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] After an applicant obtains a law degree, he or she must then undertake two years of practical training as a trainee lawyer and plead a minimum of 25 cases.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Following the completion of the training period, the applicant must obtain the recommendation of the president of the lowest court and members of the local bar association to be admitted as a lawyer.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] A law license requires a diploma in law from a legally recognized educational institution.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Ethiopian law schools offer undergraduate (LLB) and postgraduate (Juris Doctor) degrees in law.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Students must complete a college preparatory program before acceptance to an LLB program.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Those with an undergraduate degree (BA or BSC) in another field may be admitted to a three-year Juris Doctor program.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] All undergraduate students must complete the Law School Exit Examination to graduate.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] After earning a law degree, graduates must pass an exam for the relevant law license.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The Regions of Ethiopia and the Ethiopian federal government all issue their own licenses for the practice of law.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Gabon requires candidates to hold a law degree and complete a one-year internship under the supervision of a lawyer who has been licensed to practice law for at least five years.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] After completing the internship, the candidate must then petition the President of the Bar Association for a second one-year internship.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] At the end of the second internship, the candidate may petition the Bar Council to be enrolled as a lawyer.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The General Legal Council is responsible for issuing licenses to practice law.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Applicants must be of good character and have satisfactorily completed a course in law which meets its requirements at a school of law or other place of instruction it recognizes, or be qualified in practicing law in a country with a sufficiently analogous legal system.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] They must also practice for at least six months in the chambers of a lawyer who has been working in the profession for not less than seven years.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Those admitted to practice law in Ghana become members of the Ghana Bar Association.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Legal practice in Kenya is governed by the Advocates Act, Chapter 16 of the Laws of Kenya.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Only lawyers admitted to the Bar, known as Advocates of the High Court of Kenya, have the right of audience before Kenyan courts.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The petition is addressed to both the registrar of the High Court on behalf of the chief justice and the secretary/CEO of the Law Society of Kenya, and upon approval by the Council of the Law Society, one is 'called to the bar'.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The call is made in open court by taking an oath before the chief justice, who pronounces the admission.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Usually, several lawyers are admitted to the bar at the same session.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] An annual fee for a 'practising certificate' must be paid to the Law Society of Kenya, although the certificate is issued by the Court Registrar.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Non-payment renders one ineligible to appear before courts.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Lawyers who do not wish to appear before courts need not take out a certificate, but in practice most lawyers do so as it is generally required by most employers, since only advocates can sign any documents in such capacity.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] To appear before the Supreme Court, one must be an advocate of seven years' standing.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] To become an advocate (*advocat*), an individual must obtain a master's degree in law or equivalent degree and a Certificate of Aptitude for the Legal Profession, after which three years of further legal training, which can be extended by another two years, are required.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Applicants must then pass the bar exam conducted by the Ministry of Justice and practice as a trainee lawyer for two years.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Namibia has a detailed act that fully delineates the requisites to be a Legal Practitioner.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Admission to the Niger Bar requires a master's degree in law, passing the entry exam, completing a Certificate of Professional Practice and a one-year internship, or a two-year internship for those who do not have a Certificate of Professional Practice.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] At the end of the internship, the trainee lawyer is given a certificate of completion after their supervisor gives a reasoned opinion, and is eligible to register for the Niger Bar.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] One has to complete a five-year LLB program in an accredited university in Nigeria or abroad, then a compulsory one-year program (bar 2) at the Nigerian Law School.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] International students do a preliminary course (bar 1) before doing the compulsory one-year program.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] During the law school program, students do compulsory court attachment and chamber attachment before graduation.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] After obtaining a law degree, aspiring lawyers must pass the examination at the Nigerian Law School.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Those who pass are then called to the Nigerian Bar by the Nigerian Body of Benchers and enroll as a legal practitioner before the Supreme Court of Nigeria.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Holders of a Rwandan law license must be nationals of Rwanda, hold at least a bachelor's degree in law or equivalent degree, have a certificate from the Institute of Legal Practice and Development or an equivalent, and pass the bar exam.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Applicants must also not have been sentenced to a prison term equal to or exceeding six months.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] To be admitted to practice law in South Africa, one must complete a Bachelor of Laws (LLB) degree at a South African university and pass the Attorneys' Admission Exams.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] This is followed by two years of Practical Vocational Training under a Practical Vocational Training Contract (PVTC) with a law firm.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Finally, the applicant must apply to the High Court for admission and register with the Legal Practice Council.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Successful applicants must complete a one-year traineeship, then pass an interview with the Bar Admission Committee before being admitted.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] To practice as an advocate in Tunisia, individuals must be registered in the table of advocats.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Registration requires a person to have held Tunisian nationality for at least five years, to be a resident of Tunisia, be between 20 and 50 years of age, have no criminal record, never to have been declared bankrupt, and have fulfilled all national service requirements.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Candidates must hold a certificate of aptitude for the legal profession from the Higher Institute of the Legal Profession unless they hold the title of Professor of Law from a Tunisian or foreign university, in which case they may gain an exemption from this requirement.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Newly qualified lawyers must spend a year as a trainee lawyer, during which time they can only plead before lower courts.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] After one year, they may apply to be fully certified as a lawyer.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Candidates must then apply to be recognized as lawyers by the Law Council, which will issue an advocate's license if satisfied that the applicant is eligible and is a fit and proper person to be an advocate.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Advocate's licenses must be renewed annually.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] To be admitted to practice law, one must complete an LLB degree from the University of Zimbabwe or Midlands State University, register with the Law Society of Zimbabwe and receive a practicing certificate, and be enrolled on the register of the Supreme Court of Zimbabwe.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Practicing certificates from the Law Society of Zimbabwe must be renewed annually.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Holders of degrees from outside Zimbabwe must have obtained them from designated institutions and take an exam.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] English, admission to the bar is also commonly known as obtaining one's "law license" ("licence" in Canadian English).
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Admission to practice in Anguilla is regulated by the Legal Profession Act 2016.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] To be admitted in Anguilla a person first needs to be admitted in either England & Wales, Scotland or Northern Ireland, or have received a Certificate of Legal Education from the Council of Legal Education of the West Indies.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Further the applicant needs to be either (a) a Belonger of Anguilla, (b) resident in Anguilla, or (c) a citizen of certain specified Caribbean countries.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] In Argentina, prospective lawyers must complete an undergraduate law degree (Abogado, which lasts five to six years depending on the university), and then become a member of one of the jurisdictional associations.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Under the laws of the Bahamas, only a Bahamian national can normally be admitted as a lawyer.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] However, there is an exception for special admissions to allow senior barristers who have specialist expertise to be admitted to conduct a single case.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Bolivia requires candidates to complete a law degree at a Bolivian law school, which takes 9-10 semesters, and then submit a graduate certificate and certificate of good civil standing to the Ministry of Justice.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Brazil requires an undergraduate law degree (Bachelor in law, in Portuguese Bacharelado em Direito, which lasts five years) and the passing of the bar examination.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] A person may be admitted as a barrister or solicitor in the British Virgin Islands either by being admitted as a lawyer in the United Kingdom, or by attending one of the three regional law schools (Hugh Wooding Law School, Norman Manley Law School or Eugene Dupuch Law School).
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] In 2015 the British Virgin Islands passed the Legal Profession Act 2015.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The new regime will also allow senior foreign lawyers to be admitted temporarily just for a single case.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Canadian applicants to the bar must obtain admission (referred to as the "call to the bar") to one of the provincial or territorial Law Societies in the various jurisdictions of Canada.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] All domestically trained lawyers must have a bachelor's degree in law LLB or Juris Doctor (JD) from a law school accredited by the provincial law society or the National Committee on Accreditation before being called to the bar.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Admission requirements to law school vary between those of common law jurisdictions, which comprise all but one of Canada's provinces and territories, and the province of Quebec, which is a civil law jurisdiction.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] For common law schools, students must have already completed an undergraduate degree before being admitted to an LLB or JD programme, although this requirement can be waived in exceptional circumstances.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] For civil law schools, students must generally either have graduated from a general and vocational college (CEGEP), have a two-year college degree, or have completed at least a year of undergraduate education.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Once students earn a law degree, they must typically pass examinations and/or a legal training program and serve in an apprenticeship as an articled clerk with a law firm for a certain amount of time.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The exact requirements vary among the different provinces and territories.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] All jurisdictions require a law degree and a certain period of time articling.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Some require a bar exam or multiple exams, others require a bar admissions course in place of an exam, and others require both examinations and courses.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] For example, the Law Society of British Columbia requires that a student complete an undergraduate degree in any discipline and before studying for an undergraduate law degree (LL.B. and/or B.C.L., three to four years) or Juris Doctor (three years).
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The applicant must then pass two licensing examinations, the Barrister Licensing Examination and Solicitor Licensing Examination, then article with a law firm for nine to fifteen months depending on the jurisdiction and nature of the articling process.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The Law Society of Ontario likewise requires law graduates to pass a Barrister Licensing Examination and Solicitor Licensing Examination, then requires that candidates complete ten months of articles supervised by a practising lawyer, or an alternative such as an eight-month Law Practise Program.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The Bar of Quebec requires a bar exam and a 6-month articling period.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The Law Society of Yukon requires students to article for a year and during that time to attend the Bar Admissions Course and take the Yukon Statutes Exam.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] All provinces also have character and fitness requirements.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] A person may be admitted as an attorney-at-law in the Cayman Islands by one of three routes.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Under the Legal Practitioners (Students) Regulations (2012 Revision) only Caymanians or persons that hold Cayman Status or as otherwise approved by the Cayman Islands Cabinet may undertake the PPC.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Lastly, lawyers who are admitted in another jurisdiction and who only wish to be temporarily admitted in the Cayman Islands for the purposes of appearing in a single case (usually King’s Counsel from London) may be temporarily admitted.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] All attorneys are required to hold a current practicing certificate to practice law, but the Cayman Islands is slightly unusual that if an Attorney ceases to hold a practicing certificate for two years they are struck off the roll.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Chile requires a law degree (Licenciado en Ciencias Jurídicas: five years, and to pass a bar exam covering all civil and procedural law studied, which usually takes one or two years more).
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] A six-month apprenticeship is also required.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Candidates are then sworn in as a lawyer in the Supreme Court.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] In Cuba, candidates must complete a law degree.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Law school courses last five years and include several cycles of apprenticeships.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] After graduating, most students must sit the bar exam.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Those with the highest grades may be admitted to practice law by writing an honors thesis rather than taking the bar exam.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] All graduates must also perform three years of social service.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Ecuador requires a law degree from a university in Ecuador recognized by the Secretary of Higher Education, Science, Technology and Innovation.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Candidates must then complete a Pre-Professional Practice Program in a given public institution, totalling at least 500 hours of study.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] They must then register with the Lawyers' Forum of the Judicial Council.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] To be admitted as a lawyer in Guatemala, it is necessary to hold a certificate of competence issued by the Supreme Court of Justice, which is available to those who are Guatemalan nationals and have obtained a law degree from a recognized university.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Those practicing law must also register with the College of Attorneys and Notaries.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Lawyers (Abogados) in Peru must be members of a local bar association, which requires an undergraduate law degree (Bachiller en Derecho, a six-year program) and a diploma (Titulo de Abogado), the latter requiring one year of apprenticeship and passing of the bar exam.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] In the United States, all states, territories, and the District of Columbia regulate and license the legal profession separately and maintain their own bars.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] While some other Common law countries maintain separate categories of lawyers in the form of barristers and solicitors, there is only one category of lawyer in the United States.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The terms lawyer and attorney are used interchangeably.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] With varying exceptions, jurisdictions typically require that candidates complete a postgraduate law degree and pass the bar examination.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Most jurisdictions require applicants to complete a Juris Doctor degree from a law school approved by the American Bar Association (ABA).
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] In the United States, all law degrees are postgraduate.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Law schools require candidates to hold a bachelor's degree prior to commencing law studies.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] There are no requirements for any particular undergraduate degrees, and aspiring law students may complete a degree in any particular subject or in general studies.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Formal pre-law programs exist but are not typically given special favor by law schools.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] A minority of states permit graduates of law schools not approved by the ABA to take their bar examination or will admit a graduate of such a school to their bar association provided that the candidate has been admitted to the bar of another state.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The states of Alabama, California, Connecticut, Massachusetts, West Virginia, and Tennessee allow individuals to take the bar exam upon graduation from law schools approved by state bodies but not accredited by the ABA.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Specifically in California, certain law schools "registered" with the Committee of Bar Examiners of the State Bar of California (CBE) are authorized to grant Juris Doctor degrees although they are not accredited by the ABA or CBE.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Students at these schools must take and pass the First-Year Law Students' Examination (commonly referred to as the "baby bar") administered by the CBE, and may continue their studies to obtain their Juris Doctor degree upon passage of this exam.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The state of New York makes special provision for persons educated to degree-level in common law from overseas, with holders of bachelor degrees in law being qualified to take the bar exam and, upon passing, be admitted to the bar.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] All jurisdictions require applicants to pass a moral character evaluation and to pass an ethics examination, which some states administer as part of their bar examinations.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Most also require applicants to achieve a particular score on the Multistate Professional Responsibility Examination.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The states of Wisconsin and New Hampshire are the only jurisdictions to not unconditionally require law graduates to pass a bar exam for admission.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Diploma privilege is available in Wisconsin for J.D. graduates of the state's two ABA-accredited law schools.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] LLM and SJD graduates of these law schools are not eligible for diploma privilege.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] New Hampshire's only law school has an alternative licensing program that allows a limited number of students who have completed certain curricula and a separate exam to bypass the regular bar examination.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The states of California, Maine, New York, Vermont, Virginia, Washington, and West Virginia allow applicants to study under a judge or practicing attorney for an extended period of time rather than attending law school.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] This method is known as "reading law" or "reading the law".
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] New York allows applicants who read law to take the bar exam, but only if they have at least one year of law school study.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Maine allows students who completed two years of law school to serve an apprenticeship in lieu of completing their third year.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Hours spent as an employee of an attorney or judge are not counted as study.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] The American legal system is unusual in that it has no formal apprenticeship or clinical training requirements prior to admission to the bar, with a few exceptions.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Delaware requires that candidates for admission to the bar serve five months in a clerkship with a lawyer in the state.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Vermont had a similar requirement but eliminated it in 2016.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Washington requires, since 2005, that applicants must complete a minimum of four hours of approved pre-admission education.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] Some law schools have tried to rectify this lack of experience by requiring supervised "Public Service Requirements" of all graduates.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p01] States that encourage law students to undergo clinical training or perform public service in the form of pro bono representation may allow students to appear and practice in limited court settings under the supervision of an admitted attorney.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Candidates must obtain a law degree and gain a minimum of two years of legal working experience, which is often fulfilled by a legal internship.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] After completing these requirements, they may sit for the bar exam.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Those who pass may apply for membership in the bar.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Practicing law requires admission to the Bangladesh Bar Council.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] In order to do so, candidates must be citizens of Bangladesh, be a minimum of 21 years old, and obtain a law degree.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] They must pass the Bar Council Examination to be allowed to practice law.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] In Bhutan, only Bhutanese citizens are permitted to practice law; international lawyers and firms are not allowed to practice in the country.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Lawyers practicing in Bhutan, known as Jabmi in Dzongkha, must pass the Bar exam conducted by the Bar Council of Bhutan.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Cambodia requires a Bachelor of Law or equivalent law degree, certificate of Lawyer's Professional Skill from the Center for the Training of the Legal Profession, and no misdemeanor or felony record, as well as no disciplinary sanction or administrative penalty.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Unless granted an exemption, prospective lawyers must then spend a year as a trainee lawyer, either in a training program conducted by the Bar Association or by working as an associate in a law firm.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Following the training period, the Bar Council will make a decision whether or not to register the prospective lawyer with the Bar Association based on whether or not the trainee fulfilled the requirements and a report on the trainee's supervising lawyer.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] If the Bar Council decides that the trainee does not have sufficient competence, it can order a period of additional training not to exceed one year.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Applicants who satisfy the Bar Council that they are of sufficient competence are registered with the Bar Association and are allowed to practice law.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] In China, one must first obtain a recognized law degree (a bachelor's, master's, or doctoral degree) or have at least three years of work experience in certain legal institutions.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Those aspiring to be allowed to practice law must also have a record of good behavior.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Applicants must then pass the National Unified Legal Professional Qualification Examination.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] They must also complete a one-year apprenticeship before being granted a license to practice law.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] The special administrative region of Hong Kong makes a distinction between barristers and solicitors.
[src:court-of-session/admission-to-practice-law-p02] Admission to either profession requires a law degree (either the four-year LL.B. or the two-year Juris Doctor) and a Postgraduate Certificate in Laws (which requires nine months).
